Apple Earnings
--------------

From the Wall Street Journal ( https://www.wsj.com/tech/apple-aapl-q3-earni=
ngs-report-2024-5e3eb3ae ) :

Apple=E2=80=99s iPhone revenue fell for a second consecutive quarter, a sof=
t demand signal investors hope will turn around once the company releases n=
ew AI features in the fall. For its quarter ended in June, iPhone sales dec=
lined nearly 1% from the prior year to about $39.3 billion and overall Appl=
e revenue increased about 5% to $85.8 billion. Both figures beat Wall Stree=
t expectations.

Apple has also been trying to catch up to rivals in the artificial-intellig=
ence arms race, unveiling an array of new AI tools in June that investors h=
ope will encourage users to upgrade their iPhones. Microsoft, Meta Platform=
s and Alphabet have spent billions on so-called generative AI, spurred on b=
y the release of startup OpenAI=E2=80=99s ChatGPT software released in late=
 2022. The world=E2=80=99s biggest technology companies have yet to unveil =
a strategy that points to reliable AI-infused profits in the near future, e=
specially as many have ramped up spending. Apple=E2=80=99s AI strategy, as =
outlined by the company, so far has come at a far lower cost compared with =
peers but depends significantly on whether customers will be convinced to b=
uy new phones.

The narrative around Apple is, as always, about the iPhone (and, for the re=
cord, the iPhone was higher on a constant currency basis); the stock price,=
 though =E2=80=94 again, before whatever happens today =E2=80=94 told a dif=
ferent story, as Apple was up on a day most of the market was down. Call it=
 the final triumph of the =E2=80=9CServices Narrative=E2=80=9D; Jason Snell=
 wrote on Six Colors ( https://sixcolors.com/post/2024/08/existential-thoug=
hts-about-apples-reliance-on-services-revenue/ ) :

In the most recent financial quarter, Apple generated $24.4 billion in reve=
nue from Services. The Mac, iPad, and wearables categories together generat=
ed just $22.3 billion. Only the iPhone is more important to Apple=E2=80=99s=
 top line than Services. But what about the bottom line? While Apple=E2=80=
=99s Services gross margin was 74% last quarter, products was only a measly=
 35%. (I=E2=80=99m kidding=E2=80=9435% margin on hardware is actually a rea=
lly great number. It just can=E2=80=99t compare to Services, because hardwa=
re has some fundamental costs that services just don=E2=80=99t.)

Let=E2=80=99s look at total profits:

Apple's total profit dollars from products and services ( https://sixcolors=
.com/post/2024/08/existential-thoughts-about-apples-reliance-on-services-re=
venue/ )

Last quarter, Apple made about $22 billion in profit from products and $18 =
billion from Services. It=E2=80=99s the closest those two lines have ever c=
ome to each other. This is what was buzzing in the back of my head as I was=
 going over all the numbers on Thursday. We=E2=80=99re not quite there yet,=
 but it=E2=80=99s hard to imagine that there won=E2=80=99t be a quarter in =
the next year or so in which Apple reports more total profit on Services th=
an on products. When that happens, is Apple still a products company? Or ha=
s it crossed some invisible line?

Snell=E2=80=99s Article does, as you might expect from a longtime Apple obs=
erver, focus more on the existential nature of what it means for Apple to b=
e a product company versus a services company; he concludes =E2=80=94 and I=
 agree =E2=80=94 that it is important for Apple to remain focused on produc=
ts because that is what drives the services revenue. That noted, the stella=
r nature of these results, and the fact that Apple was duly rewarded for sa=
id results, even in the face of iPhone softness, speaks to the extent to wh=
ich the fundamental understanding of the company has changed when it comes =
to its finances.

One additional note on that ongoing bugaboo, China; from the question-and-a=
nswer portion of the earnings call ( https://sixcolors.com/post/2024/08/thi=
s-is-tim-q3-2024-analyst-call-transcript/ ) :

*Can you maybe dig into the China dynamics a bit? Sales down 6% this quarte=
r, 3% in constant currency. An improvement from last quarter on a tougher c=
ompare, you know, that came on the back of some iPhone discounting. So can =
you maybe just share color on the China market as a whole, how much you bel=
ieve promotions helped in the quarter, how sustainable this improvement is,=
 and if this performance really changes any of your approach to the China m=
arket as we look forward.*

*Tim Cook:* Yeah, Eric, as you point out, we decreased by six and a half pe=
rcent year over year for the whole of greater China, and if you look at it =
on a constant currency basis, we declined by less than three. So over 50 pe=
rcent of the decline year over year is currency related. That is an improve=
ment from the first half of the fiscal year and so we=E2=80=99re happy to s=
ee the acceleration.

If you look at iPhone in particular for Greater China, the installed base s=
et a record. We also in mainland China set a June quarter record for upgrad=
ers and so that=E2=80=99s a very strong signal, and in fact, the survey fro=
m Kantar this quarter showed that iPhones were the top three models in urba=
n China. Also, one of the things we look at is the 15 family compared to th=
e 14 family for the same number of weeks from launch. So this goes all the =
way back to September of =E2=80=9923. If you if you look at that, the 15 is=
 outperforming the 14, and and so those are some of the some of the color I=
 would provide.

In addition, one of the things that we=E2=80=99re very focused on is the le=
vel of new customers buying our products, and so if you look at this on the=
 Mac and iPad, in mainland China the majority of customers buying are buyin=
g that product for the first time, and the Watch, the vast, vast majority o=
f people are buying the product for the first time. And during the quarter,=
 I should say also, that iPad returned to growth in greater China as it did=
 around the world. And so we continue to be confident in the long-term oppo=
rtunity in China. I don=E2=80=99t know how every chapter of the book reads =
but we=E2=80=99re we=E2=80=99re very confident in the long term.

Cook is saying a number of things that are incongruous, at least at first b=
lush: China sales are down, Apple is setting a record for iPhone upgraders,=
 and he highlighted the number of new customers buying their products; thos=
e three things can=E2=80=99t be happening at the same time! What squares th=
e circle, I think, is that the examples of new customers buying Apple produ=
cts were Mac, iPad, and Watch. My strong suspicion is that those may be new=
 customers to those products, but that they already own iPhones; in other w=
ords, Apple is doing a good job of holding onto its existing customer base =
(iPhone upgrades), and even deepening their ARPU with that base (by selling=
 them other Apple products), but is probably struggling to acquire customer=
s who are completely new to Apple.

Meta Earnings
-------------

From Bloomberg ( https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2024-07-31/meta-re=
ports-better-than-expected-quarterly-advertising-sales ) :

Meta Platforms Inc. reported better-than-expected sales in the second quart=
er on Wednesday, signaling that the company=E2=80=99s investments in artifi=
cial intelligence are helping it sell more targeted ads. Shares jumped in T=
hursday trading. That progress is buying Chief Executive Officer Mark Zucke=
rberg more time to prove that his bets on the metaverse and AI are worth th=
eir while. In a call with investors and analysts on Wednesday, he expounded=
 on Meta=E2=80=99s push into the type of large language models that power A=
I chatbots and praised the company=E2=80=99s AI smart glasses and virtual r=
eality headsets.

Two weeks ago, I urged you ( https://stratechery.com/2024/llama-3-1-zuckerb=
erg-on-open-source-ai-kamala-harris-europe-and-tech-innovation/?access_toke=
n=3DeyJhbGciOiJSUzI1NiIsImtpZCI6InN0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LnBhc3Nwb3J0Lm9ubGluZSIsInR=
