iwic2NvcGUiOiJmZWVkOnJlYWQgYXJ0aWNsZTpyZWFkIGFzc2V0OnJlYWQgY2F0ZWdvcnk6cmVh=
ZCBlbnRpdGxlbWVudHMiLCJzdWIiOiJSc2V1WUU4amdIZVBwV0pmMWZBYjRDIiwidXNlIjoiYWN=
jZXNzIn0.SYKg00YC2YMpWQylWD4w7Y9etynl92YHM5_3RGCpyU4JH-EQR7VDgYbz-VV8VfnHNl=
Q7UeH4olhYNrNxLlksOJnDaPyp862sqR1mA9XaurxtEXlhBZfsDqwDKdf_g_1IkWFquOcecYnWa=
RM4QQg3piPdKHV1pGEO3SJER80w0CuMMlxFSzAw07mcnZc8oyYDGmEAan0PDJl5jUU1gHX0-a57=
i1YHxY7rrZUSjSLC0mszlS_K-pxyzFFsZMeq0hgvV46FMrjnLvTF-DYkLE-t7dlQMjE4wkwC3AX=
qFuGQMgFdSOAvGKOIfMVnLz7kggHzRyVhE3zFb94KdQgqVcqyLA ) to read Zuckerberg=E2=
=80=99s post about open source (weights) models ( https://about.fb.com/news=
/2024/07/open-source-ai-is-the-path-forward/ ) ; I think that his comments =
on the company=E2=80=99s earnings call ( https://s21.q4cdn.com/399680738/fi=
les/doc_financials/2024/q2/META-Q2-2024-Earnings-Call-Transcript.pdf ) is a=
 useful addendum. I was quite impressed with the clarity of Zuckerberg=E2=
=80=99s vision for AI. From those comments:

The big theme right now is of course AI, and I=E2=80=99ll focus my comments=
 today on three areas: what AI means for our family of apps and core busine=
ss, what new AI experiences and opportunities we see, and how AI is shaping=
 our metaverse work.

The core business opportunities was the most compelling, because they are b=
oth concrete and believable. Zuckerberg argued that AI:

* Helps Meta improve recommendations and drive engagement.
* Will drive a more valuable advertising product by generating ads better t=
han advertisers can on their own, augmenting Meta=E2=80=99s demonstrated ab=
ility to do a better job of finding customers than advertisers can on their=
 own.
* Make messaging a more viable option for businesses in markets with higher=
 labor costs (which are also markets with higher advertising budgets), driv=
ing click-to-message ads.

I=E2=80=99m on board with all of these; Zuckerberg also talked about the po=
tential of Meta AI, and while that is interesting, what I think is importan=
t for Meta=E2=80=99s business is that Meta AI adoption and eventual monetiz=
ation is option value on top of concrete applications that are easy to envi=
sion driving meaningful business results. To that end, I thought this bit f=
rom Zuckerberg in the question-and-answer portion of the call was notable:

I think for those who have followed our business for a long time, you can a=
lso get a pretty good sense of when things are going to work years in advan=
ce. And I think that the people who bet on those early indicators tend to d=
o pretty well which is why I wanted to share in my comments the early indic=
ator that we had on Meta AI, which is, I mean look, it=E2=80=99s early. Las=
t quarter, I think it just started rolling it out a week or two before our =
earnings call. This time, we=E2=80=99re a few months later. And what we can=
 say is I think we are on track to achieve our goal of being the most used =
AI assistant by the end of this year. And I think that=E2=80=99s a pretty b=
ig deal. Is that the only thing we want to do? No. I mean we obviously want=
 to kind of grow that and grow the engagement on that to be a lot deeper, a=
nd then we=E2=80=99ll focus on monetizing it over time. But the early signa=
ls on this are good, and I think that that=E2=80=99s kind of all that we co=
uld reasonably have insight into at this point.

But I do think that part of what=E2=80=99s so fundamental about AI is it=E2=
=80=99s going to end up affecting almost every product that we have in some=
 way. It will improve the existing ones and will make a whole lot of new on=
es possible. So it=E2=80=99s why there are all the jokes about how all the =
tech CEOs get on these earnings calls and just talk about AI the whole time=
. It=E2=80=99s because it=E2=80=99s actually super exciting, and it=E2=80=
=99s going to change all these different things over multiple time horizons=
.

This gets at the thesis I started developing last week ( https://stratecher=
y.com/2024/microsoft-earnings-copilot-and-capex-pichai-on-risk/?access_toke=
n=3DeyJhbGciOiJSUzI1NiIsImtpZCI6InN0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LnBhc3Nwb3J0Lm9ubGluZSIsInR=
5cCI6IkpXVCJ9.eyJhdWQiOiJzdHJhdGVjaGVyeS5wYXNzcG9ydC5vbmxpbmUiLCJhenAiOiJIS=
0xjUzREd1Nod1AyWURLYmZQV00xIiwiZW50Ijp7InVyaSI6WyJodHRwczovL3N0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5=
LmNvbS8yMDI0L21pY3Jvc29mdC1lYXJuaW5ncy1jb3BpbG90LWFuZC1jYXBleC1waWNoYWktb24=
tcmlzay8iXX0sImV4cCI6MTcyNTQ0NjkwNywiaWF0IjoxNzIyODU0OTA3LCJpc3MiOiJodHRwcz=
ovL2FwaS5wYXNzcG9ydC5vbmxpbmUvb2F1dGgiLCJzY29wZSI6ImZlZWQ6cmVhZCBhcnRpY2xlO=
nJlYWQgYXNzZXQ6cmVhZCBjYXRlZ29yeTpyZWFkIGVudGl0bGVtZW50cyIsInN1YiI6IlJzZXVZ=
RThqZ0hlUHBXSmYxZkFiNEMiLCJ1c2UiOiJhY2Nlc3MifQ.ToVWt8LAVmzWwgfcjw0_fpv-EHo8=
R-SR-oqAUyZ8yRK4c6knKSoevHxnwRViSeEY7jlBdpeT-N7CwyQXmR-tDI7KnmgqP45QCMDuVOK=
fHGzd3Qh93ASJU1wx4mSz8CO_lv5d5C3c_1K2aSrz_xBUz287ecHcwFkXAhTpbxHHXbA3U3BIwv=
1gs4uuHS3QonrRyoLW1Q9l-VWRSfkiySbvDSRoJUutJ5rziD69w71BZBLlLIKznrC2Udj02__Bw=
8bcT6RdM8bW1X3iRktik_iVYHAZj43PSif2Aplyfchz-dcn2eBrpE0F_yGbkSdE8uIb4Aln3kIW=
aeA9m9BK9fyozQ ) about the relative position/risk profile of the big tech c=
ompanies when it comes to AI. One view is that generative AI is a major fea=
ture that will drive a widespread boon in new products and companies; that =
is good news for companies selling AI capacity. Another view is that AI is =
a tool that makes existing products better, which favors companies that hav=
e products that can be made better by AI. My view is increasingly the latte=
r, which is good for Meta because, as Zuckerberg laid out, they have very o=
bvious things to build that can leverage AI in ways that directly impact th=
eir financial results.

What is clear is that Meta =E2=80=94 like everyone else =E2=80=94 is commit=
ted to building. Zuckerberg said:

Another major area of focus is figuring out the right level of infra capaci=
ty to support training more and more advanced models. Llama 3 is already co=
mpetitive with the most advanced models, and we=E2=80=99re already starting=
 to work on Llama 4, which we=E2=80=99re aiming to be the most advanced in =
the industry next year. We=E2=80=99re planning for the compute clusters and=
 data we=E2=80=99ll need for the next several years. The amount of compute =
needed to train Llama 4 will likely be almost 10x more than what we used to=
 train Llama 3 =E2=80=94 and future models will continue to grow beyond tha=
t. It=E2=80=99s hard to predict how this will trend multiple generations ou=
t into the future, but at this point I=E2=80=99d rather risk building capac=
ity before it is needed, rather than too late, given the long lead times fo=
r spinning up new infra projects. And as we scale these investments, we=E2=
=80=99re of course going to remain committed to operational efficiency acro=
ss the company.

Investors may be nervous about all of this capex, but as I have been noting=
 for a while now, I=E2=80=99m gaining a much more visceral understanding of=
 how bubbles =E2=80=94 to the extent there is or will be one =E2=80=94 come=
 to be: everyone is convinced that the real risk is in not building enough,=
 not in building too much. We are indeed all learning a lot more about the =
1990s!

